04621nam a22006135i 9780674034228DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221998mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740342287 a10.4159/97806740342282doi  a(DE-B1597)574405  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHX264.7.L34 ǂb D46 1998eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a335.40921 aDerfler, Leslie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPaul Lafargue and the Flowering of French Socialism, 1882–1911 /cLeslie Derfler. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (397 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Faults Enough and to Spare -- t2 Defending the Faith -- t3 Beyond All Possible Bounds -- t4 The Parisians Have Gone Mad -- t5 That Damned Congress -- t6 Fusillade at Fourmies -- t7 A Dangerous Dream -- t8 Peasants and Patriots -- t9 Beaten But Not Stoned -- t10 Let Us Storm the Forts -- t11 The Myth That Seems Absurd -- t12 Pleasantries or Naïvetés -- t13 Absurd and Incredible Conduct -- t14 Party of Opposition -- t15 Socialism and the Intellectuals -- t16 A Force Retarding Human Progress -- t17 The Unperceived Force -- t18 One Reform on Top of Another -- t19 Simply ... Logical -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPaul Lafargue, the disciple and son-in-law of Karl Marx, helped to found the first French Marxist party in 1882. Over the next three decades, he served as the chief theoretician and propagandist for Marxism in France. During these years, which ended with the dramatic suicides of Lafargue and his wife, French socialism, and the Marxist party within it, became a significant political force. In an earlier volume, Paul Lafargue and the Founding of French Marxism, 1842-1882, Leslie Derfler emphasized family identity and the origin of French Marxism. Here, he explores Lafargue's political strategies, specifically his break with party co-founder Jules Guesde in the Boulanger and Dreyfus episodes and over the question of socialist-syndicalist relations. Derfler shows Lafargue's importance as both political activist and theorist. He describes Lafargue's role in the formulation of such strategies as the promotion of a Second Workingmen's International, the pursuit of reform within the framework of the existent state but opposition to any socialist participation in nonsocialist governments, and the subordination of trade unionism to political action. He emphasizes Lafargue's pioneering efforts to apply Marxist methods of analysis to questions of anthropology, aesthetics, and literary criticism. Despite the crucial part they played in the social and political changes of the past century and the heritage they left, the first French Marxists are not widely known, especially in the English-speaking world. This important critical biography of Lafargue, the most audacious of their much maligned theorists, enables us to trace the options open to Marxist socialism as well as its development during a critical period of transition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674034228423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674034228/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aP